39
00:01:29,400 --> 00:01:33,680
scheduler. By far the simplest CPU

40
00:01:31,840 --> 00:01:35,920
scheduling algorithm is the first come

41
00:01:33,680 --> 00:01:38,000
first serve scheduling algorithm. With

42
00:01:35,920 --> 00:01:40,880
this scheme, the CPU is allocated to the

43
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:42,479
first process that requested it. To

44
00:01:40,880 --> 00:01:44,759
begin with, we must be clear about what

45
00:01:42,479 --> 00:01:47,600
it means to allocate the CPU to a

46
00:01:44,759 --> 00:01:49,600
process. When a program is executed, it

47
00:01:47,600 --> 00:01:52,320
becomes a process and the operating

48
00:01:49,600 --> 00:01:54,000
system reserves a memory block for it.

49
00:01:52,320 --> 00:01:56,240
Within this block, there's a memory

50
00:01:54,000 --> 00:01:58,200
segment called the text section which

51
00:01:56,240 --> 00:02:00,560
contains the executable code for the

52
00:01:58,200 --> 00:02:02,840
program. Each process has its own

53
00:02:00,560 --> 00:02:05,360
dedicated text

54
00:02:02,840 --> 00:02:07,119
section. From our computer architecture

55
00:02:05,360 --> 00:02:09,200
from scratch course, we know that the

56
00:02:07,119 --> 00:02:11,599
CPU contains a special register called

57
00:02:09,200 --> 00:02:14,000
the address register, also known as the

58
00:02:11,599 --> 00:02:16,160
program counter. This register points to

59
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:18,560
the next instruction to be executed.

60
00:02:16,160 --> 00:02:20,720
When we say the CPU is allocated to a

61
00:02:18,560 --> 00:02:22,400
process, it means that this register is

62
00:02:20,720 --> 00:02:25,120
pointing to the text section of that

63
00:02:22,400 --> 00:02:27,920
process enabling the CPU to execute

64
00:02:25,120 --> 00:02:30,000
instructions from it. When the CPU is

65
00:02:27,920 --> 00:02:31,920
reallocated to another process, the

66
00:02:30,000 --> 00:02:34,160
operating system modifies the address

67
00:02:31,920 --> 00:02:37,200
register so it points to the executable

68
00:02:34,160 --> 00:02:39,519
code of the new process. This involves a

69
00:02:37,200 --> 00:02:41,280
more complex operation called a context

70
00:02:39,519 --> 00:02:45,239
switch, which we've covered with more

71
00:02:41,280 --> 00:02:45,239
details in previous episodes.

72
00:02:46,640 --> 00:02:50,640
Another important concept to understand

73
00:02:48,640 --> 00:02:53,040
is that processes aren't concrete

74
00:02:50,640 --> 00:02:54,879
entities like objects or instances of

75
00:02:53,040 --> 00:02:57,760
structures in the traditional computer

76
00:02:54,879 --> 00:03:00,000
science sense. Instead, processes are

77
00:02:57,760 --> 00:03:02,239
contexts in which the computer operates.

78
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:04,080
To manage these processes, the operating

79
00:03:02,239 --> 00:03:07,920
system uses a special structure called

80
00:03:04,080 --> 00:03:10,000
the process control block or PCB.

81
00:03:07,920 --> 00:03:12,159
This strct is not the process itself,

82
00:03:10,000 --> 00:03:14,000
but rather a representation of it

83
00:03:12,159 --> 00:03:16,400
containing all the necessary information

84
00:03:14,000 --> 00:03:18,800
about the process such as its state,

85
00:03:16,400 --> 00:03:19,800
program counter, registers, and other

86
00:03:18,800 --> 00:03:22,400
management

87
00:03:19,800 --> 00:03:24,400
data. Every time a process is created,

88
00:03:22,400 --> 00:03:26,239
the operating system generates a process

89
00:03:24,400 --> 00:03:28,800
control block to keep track of that new

90
00:03:26,239 --> 00:03:30,799
process. The implementation of the first

91
00:03:28,800 --> 00:03:33,599
come first serve policy is easily

92
00:03:30,799 --> 00:03:35,040
managed with a FIFO Q which makes sense

93
00:03:33,599 --> 00:03:36,640
here because it operates on the

94
00:03:35,040 --> 00:03:38,760
principle that the first element added

95
00:03:36,640 --> 00:03:41,280
to the queue is the first one to be

96
00:03:38,760 --> 00:03:42,799
removed. But we cannot directly push

97
00:03:41,280 --> 00:03:45,200
processes into this queue because

98
00:03:42,799 --> 00:03:47,040
processes are abstract contexts and

99
00:03:45,200 --> 00:03:49,599
cannot be treated as discrete elements

100
00:03:47,040 --> 00:03:51,440
of any data structure. Instead, what the

101
00:03:49,599 --> 00:03:53,360
operating system does is push the

102
00:03:51,440 --> 00:03:55,680
process control block of each process

103
00:03:53,360 --> 00:03:58,640
into the queue. Throughout this video,

104
00:03:55,680 --> 00:04:00,879
I'll represent PCBs as boxes. And you'll

105
00:03:58,640 --> 00:04:03,120
often, if not almost always, hear me

106
00:04:00,879 --> 00:04:04,720
refer to them as processes. But remember

107
00:04:03,120 --> 00:04:06,720
that what enters the queue isn't

108
00:04:04,720 --> 00:04:09,439
actually a process, but its process

109
00:04:06,720 --> 00:04:11,680
control block. In first come, first

110
00:04:09,439 --> 00:04:13,519
serve. When a process is created, its

111
00:04:11,680 --> 00:04:16,079
process control block is pushed onto the

112
00:04:13,519 --> 00:04:18,000
tail of the que. When the CPU is free,

113
00:04:16,079 --> 00:04:21,519
it is allocated to the process at the

114
00:04:18,000 --> 00:04:23,360
head of the queue. Sounds simple, right?

115
00:04:21,519 --> 00:04:25,759
Well, not quite. There's a lot we're

116
00:04:23,360 --> 00:04:27,600
overlooking. For starters, we are

117
00:04:25,759 --> 00:04:29,680
assuming that a process can only get the

118
00:04:27,600 --> 00:04:31,000
CPU once the previous process has

119
00:04:29,680 --> 00:04:33,639
completed its

120
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:36,320
execution. This causes a lot of

121
00:04:33,639 --> 00:04:38,720
problems. First, not all processes

122
00:04:36,320 --> 00:04:40,800
terminate. Many applications such as

123
00:04:38,720 --> 00:04:43,120
servers or background services are

124
00:04:40,800 --> 00:04:45,280
designed to run indefinitely. If we

125
00:04:43,120 --> 00:04:47,759
allocate the CPU to a process that never

126
00:04:45,280 --> 00:04:50,479
ends, all subsequent processes would be

127
00:04:47,759 --> 00:04:52,720
indefinitely waiting in the queue.

128
00:04:50,479 --> 00:04:54,880
And second, if we assume that a process

129
00:04:52,720 --> 00:04:57,360
can only get the CPU once the previous

130
00:04:54,880 --> 00:04:59,840
process finishes its execution, we

131
00:04:57,360 --> 00:05:02,280
ignore an important fact. Programs in

132
00:04:59,840 --> 00:05:04,639
execution don't use the CPU

133
00:05:02,280 --> 00:05:06,560
continuously. If a task takes 2 minutes

134
00:05:04,639 --> 00:05:09,120
to execute, it doesn't mean it kept the

135
00:05:06,560 --> 00:05:11,039
CPU busy for the entire 2 minutes.

136
00:05:09,120 --> 00:05:12,800
During execution, there are often

137
00:05:11,039 --> 00:05:13,560
periods where the program is waiting for

138
00:05:12,800 --> 00:05:16,320
something

139
00:05:13,560 --> 00:05:19,039
else. To illustrate this, let's break it

