193
00:07:19,680 --> 00:07:22,800
Reading from and writing to files

194
00:07:21,199 --> 00:07:24,960
requires the program to invoke the

195
00:07:22,800 --> 00:07:27,120
operating system as file manipulation

196
00:07:24,960 --> 00:07:29,919
involves interacting with hardware, in

197
00:07:27,120 --> 00:07:32,120
this case the disk. In other words,

198
00:07:29,919 --> 00:07:34,160
reading and writing involve IO

199
00:07:32,120 --> 00:07:36,639
operations. The real problem here is

200
00:07:34,160 --> 00:07:38,479
that IO operations are usually costly in

201
00:07:36,639 --> 00:07:40,800
terms of performance. They can take a

202
00:07:38,479 --> 00:07:42,400
lot to complete.

203
00:07:40,800 --> 00:07:44,400
These instructions right here simply

204
00:07:42,400 --> 00:07:46,800
cannot be executed immediately after the

205
00:07:44,400 --> 00:07:48,720
previous one. Not until the IO operation

206
00:07:46,800 --> 00:07:50,479
managed by the system call is completed,

207
00:07:48,720 --> 00:07:54,080
which entirely depends on the IO

208
00:07:50,479 --> 00:07:56,440
hardware capabilities, not the CPU. As a

209
00:07:54,080 --> 00:07:58,879
result, the program doesn't use the CPU

210
00:07:56,440 --> 00:08:01,039
continuously. If we were to map CPU

211
00:07:58,879 --> 00:08:03,360
usage of a program over time, we would

212
00:08:01,039 --> 00:08:05,280
see gaps where the CPU remains idle,

213
00:08:03,360 --> 00:08:07,919
waiting for IO operations to finish

214
00:08:05,280 --> 00:08:10,080
before continuing execution.

215
00:08:07,919 --> 00:08:12,479
These gaps are not the exception but the

216
00:08:10,080 --> 00:08:14,720
norm at least in systems based on the

217
00:08:12,479 --> 00:08:17,840
vonoman architecture which represents

218
00:08:14,720 --> 00:08:19,680
over 99% of modern computers. In fact,

219
00:08:17,840 --> 00:08:22,280
this behavior is so common that it has

220
00:08:19,680 --> 00:08:24,800
been continuously studied for

221
00:08:22,280 --> 00:08:27,360
decades. Those lapses when a program is

222
00:08:24,800 --> 00:08:29,120
using the CPU are called CPU bursts

223
00:08:27,360 --> 00:08:31,039
while those time-lapses when the program

224
00:08:29,120 --> 00:08:34,080
is waiting for an IO operation to

225
00:08:31,039 --> 00:08:36,320
complete are called IO bursts. Every

226
00:08:34,080 --> 00:08:39,279
process execution begins with a CPU

227
00:08:36,320 --> 00:08:41,599
burst. that is followed by an IO burst

228
00:08:39,279 --> 00:08:44,720
which is followed by another CPU burst

229
00:08:41,599 --> 00:08:47,040
then another IO burst and so on.

230
00:08:44,720 --> 00:08:50,000
Eventually the final CPU burst ends with

231
00:08:47,040 --> 00:08:52,080
a system request to terminate execution.

232
00:08:50,000 --> 00:08:54,160
As I mentioned earlier, this behavior

233
00:08:52,080 --> 00:08:56,240
has been studied for decades as the

234
00:08:54,160 --> 00:08:58,880
success of CPU scheduling largely

235
00:08:56,240 --> 00:09:00,880
depends on it. The durations of CPU

236
00:08:58,880 --> 00:09:02,640
bursts have been extensively measured.

237
00:09:00,880 --> 00:09:04,720
And while they vary between processes

238
00:09:02,640 --> 00:09:08,279
and systems, they tend to follow a

239
00:09:04,720 --> 00:09:11,440
predictable distribution that looks like

240
00:09:08,279 --> 00:09:13,360
this. This next part is very important.

241
00:09:11,440 --> 00:09:15,120
Before continuing, take a moment to

242
00:09:13,360 --> 00:09:17,440
pause the video and analyze what this

243
00:09:15,120 --> 00:09:17,440
chart

244
00:09:18,839 --> 00:09:22,800
represents. The chart shows that most

245
00:09:21,040 --> 00:09:25,200
processes have a large number of short

246
00:09:22,800 --> 00:09:28,000
CPU bursts and only a small number of

247
00:09:25,200 --> 00:09:30,160
long CPU bursts. This is a critical

248
00:09:28,000 --> 00:09:32,160
observation for designing CPU scheduling

249
00:09:30,160 --> 00:09:34,160
algorithms because it highlights that

250
00:09:32,160 --> 00:09:37,040
processes often spend significant time

251
00:09:34,160 --> 00:09:38,720
waiting for IO operations. If a

252
00:09:37,040 --> 00:09:41,560
scheduling algorithm doesn't account for

253
00:09:38,720 --> 00:09:44,320
this behavior, a lot of CPU time will be

254
00:09:41,560 --> 00:09:46,560
wasted. So when a process enters an IO

255
00:09:44,320 --> 00:09:48,480
burst, ideally the CPU should be

256
00:09:46,560 --> 00:09:50,160
allocated to a different process, one

257
00:09:48,480 --> 00:09:52,399
that isn't also waiting for IO

258
00:09:50,160 --> 00:09:54,320
operations.

259
00:09:52,399 --> 00:09:56,800
One of the main goals of CPU scheduling

260
00:09:54,320 --> 00:09:58,640
is to keep the CPU as busy as possible,

261
00:09:56,800 --> 00:10:00,680
allowing processes to run as fast as

262
00:09:58,640 --> 00:10:03,920
they can while sharing the

263
00:10:00,680 --> 00:10:05,519
CPU. Notice that a process's CPU burst

264
00:10:03,920 --> 00:10:07,680
never starts immediately after the

265
00:10:05,519 --> 00:10:09,680
previous one ends. There is always a

266
00:10:07,680 --> 00:10:11,839
small additional process in between

267
00:10:09,680 --> 00:10:13,760
which I've represented in gray. I'll

268
00:10:11,839 --> 00:10:15,279
come back to this in a moment. What's

269
00:10:13,760 --> 00:10:17,120
important to understand right now is

270
00:10:15,279 --> 00:10:19,360
that a scheduling algorithm must take

271
00:10:17,120 --> 00:10:21,440
this into account. Instead of allocating

272
00:10:19,360 --> 00:10:23,680
the CPU to a process until it fully

273
00:10:21,440 --> 00:10:25,760
terminates, theuler should allocate it

274
00:10:23,680 --> 00:10:28,720
only until the process's current CPU

275
00:10:25,760 --> 00:10:30,079
burst ends. Achieving this behavior, of

276
00:10:28,720 --> 00:10:32,399
course, makes the implementation of

277
00:10:30,079 --> 00:10:34,160
ouruler a little more complex because

278
00:10:32,399 --> 00:10:36,720
now we need to consider that processes

279
00:10:34,160 --> 00:10:39,040
can be in different states. Every

280
00:10:36,720 --> 00:10:40,720
process begins in the new state. A new

281
00:10:39,040 --> 00:10:42,720
process is a program that has just been

282
00:10:40,720 --> 00:10:45,279
launched, but its executable file is

283
00:10:42,720 --> 00:10:46,640
still being loaded into memory. Once the

284
00:10:45,279 --> 00:10:48,560
program is fully loaded and all

285
00:10:46,640 --> 00:10:50,560
necessary resources are allocated, the

286
00:10:48,560 --> 00:10:52,160
process enters the ready state, meaning

287
00:10:50,560 --> 00:10:55,600
it is prepared to execute, but is

288
00:10:52,160 --> 00:10:57,839
waiting for CPU time. When the CPU is

289
00:10:55,600 --> 00:10:58,680
assigned to a process, it enters the

290
00:10:57,839 --> 00:11:01,440
running

291
00:10:58,680 --> 00:11:04,000
state. At some point, the process will

292
00:11:01,440 --> 00:11:06,160
likely make a system call, such as an IO

293
00:11:04,000 --> 00:11:08,440
request, which voluntarily returns

294
00:11:06,160 --> 00:11:11,040
control of the CPU to the operating

295
00:11:08,440 --> 00:11:12,880
system. Keep in mind that an IO call is

296
00:11:11,040 --> 00:11:14,880
not only made to request some resource,

297
00:11:12,880 --> 00:11:16,800
like manipulating a file or allocating

298
00:11:14,880 --> 00:11:18,560
memory, but to simply wait for some

299
00:11:16,800 --> 00:11:20,440
event to happen, such as an user

300
00:11:18,560 --> 00:11:22,800
keystroke or an incoming network

301
00:11:20,440 --> 00:11:24,399
request. In both cases, the process

302
00:11:22,800 --> 00:11:26,640
moves to the waiting state until the

303
00:11:24,399 --> 00:11:28,480
event happens or the IO operation is

304
00:11:26,640 --> 00:11:30,240
completed. Once the request is

305
00:11:28,480 --> 00:11:32,480
fulfilled, the process becomes ready

306
00:11:30,240 --> 00:11:33,640
again, waiting for theuler to allocate

307
00:11:32,480 --> 00:11:36,240
CPU

308
00:11:33,640 --> 00:11:38,399
time. Notice that even when the IO

309
00:11:36,240 --> 00:11:41,040
operation is completed, the process does

310
00:11:38,399 --> 00:11:42,720
not immediately resume execution. This

311
00:11:41,040 --> 00:11:44,880
happens because while the process was

312
00:11:42,720 --> 00:11:47,680
waiting, the CPU has most likely been

313
00:11:44,880 --> 00:11:49,200
allocated to another process. So even

314
00:11:47,680 --> 00:11:52,000
though it is now ready to continue

315
00:11:49,200 --> 00:11:54,240
running, it must wait for its turn. For

316
00:11:52,000 --> 00:11:56,480
most of their lifetime, processes cycle

317
00:11:54,240 --> 00:11:59,680
between these three states: ready,

318
00:11:56,480 --> 00:12:01,920
running, and waiting. Some processes,

319
00:11:59,680 --> 00:12:03,959
such as web servers, are designed never

320
00:12:01,920 --> 00:12:05,920
to terminate and remain in this cycle

321
00:12:03,959 --> 00:12:08,000
indefinitely. But for most user

322
00:12:05,920 --> 00:12:09,560
programs, the process eventually enters

323
00:12:08,000 --> 00:12:12,079
the terminated

324
00:12:09,560 --> 00:12:14,399
state. These names are arbitrary and

325
00:12:12,079 --> 00:12:16,000
they vary across operating systems. The

326
00:12:14,399 --> 00:12:18,880
states that they represent are found on

327
00:12:16,000 --> 00:12:21,040
all systems. However, certain operating

328
00:12:18,880 --> 00:12:23,839
systems also more finely delineate

329
00:12:21,040 --> 00:12:25,720
process states. For example, a

330
00:12:23,839 --> 00:12:28,000
terminated process may not be really

331
00:12:25,720 --> 00:12:30,320
terminated. After making a system call

332
00:12:28,000 --> 00:12:33,680
to exit, the operating system must free

333
00:12:30,320 --> 00:12:35,440
allocated resources, including memory.

334
00:12:33,680 --> 00:12:37,040
Some operating systems make a clear

335
00:12:35,440 --> 00:12:38,720
distinction between a process that has

336
00:12:37,040 --> 00:12:41,920
been fully terminated and one that is

337
00:12:38,720 --> 00:12:44,079
still in the process of termination.

338
00:12:41,920 --> 00:12:45,920
This state model explains why cues are

339
00:12:44,079 --> 00:12:48,560
the fundamental data structure used in

340
00:12:45,920 --> 00:12:50,720
CPU scheduling. Even though there is a

341
00:12:48,560 --> 00:12:52,639
specific waiting state, processes in

342
00:12:50,720 --> 00:12:55,200
other states except the running state

343
00:12:52,639 --> 00:12:57,360
are also waiting. Given that hundreds of

344
00:12:55,200 --> 00:12:59,279
processes may be waiting at any moment,

345
00:12:57,360 --> 00:13:01,639
using cues to manage their execution

346
00:12:59,279 --> 00:13:03,839
order is both logical and

347
00:13:01,639 --> 00:13:05,680
efficient. It is important to realize

348
00:13:03,839 --> 00:13:08,320
that only one process can be running on

349
00:13:05,680 --> 00:13:09,920
a processor core at any given time. This

350
00:13:08,320 --> 00:13:12,160
means that while a Q makes sense for

351
00:13:09,920 --> 00:13:14,959
waiting processes, it does not apply to

352
00:13:12,160 --> 00:13:16,720
the running process. When studying CPU

353
00:13:14,959 --> 00:13:18,480
scheduling algorithms, it is necessary

354
00:13:16,720 --> 00:13:21,480
to be aware of another component of the

355
00:13:18,480 --> 00:13:23,519
operating system, the

356
00:13:21,480 --> 00:13:25,680
dispatcher. When a running process

357
00:13:23,519 --> 00:13:27,839
enters an IO waiting state and the CPU

358
00:13:25,680 --> 00:13:30,480
becomes available, the dispatcher steps

359
00:13:27,839 --> 00:13:32,320
in with one single purpose. Allocate the

360
00:13:30,480 --> 00:13:35,279
CPU to the process at the head of the

361
00:13:32,320 --> 00:13:37,839
ready Q. In other words, perform the

362
00:13:35,279 --> 00:13:40,079
context switch. Although the running

363
00:13:37,839 --> 00:13:41,920
process is not stored in any queue, a

364
00:13:40,079 --> 00:13:44,399
reference to its process control block

365
00:13:41,920 --> 00:13:46,560
is always maintained. This allows the

366
00:13:44,399 --> 00:13:49,279
dispatcher to save the CPU state into

367
00:13:46,560 --> 00:13:51,200
the PCB when an interruption occurs.

368
00:13:49,279 --> 00:13:53,440
This saved state enables the process to

369
00:13:51,200 --> 00:13:55,560
resume execution later. The dispatcher

370
00:13:53,440 --> 00:13:57,920
then places the PCB into the waiting

371
00:13:55,560 --> 00:14:00,160
queue. Next, after handling the

372
00:13:57,920 --> 00:14:02,320
interrupted process, the dispatcher

373
00:14:00,160 --> 00:14:04,880
retrieves the PCB of the next process

374
00:14:02,320 --> 00:14:07,440
from the head of the ready Q, identifies

375
00:14:04,880 --> 00:14:09,839
it as the new running process, restores

376
00:14:07,440 --> 00:14:12,320
its previous CPU state, including

377
00:14:09,839 --> 00:14:14,560
registers and the program counter, and

378
00:14:12,320 --> 00:14:16,320
reallocates the CPU, allowing the

379
00:14:14,560 --> 00:14:18,800
process to resume execution from where

380
00:14:16,320 --> 00:14:20,639
it was interrupted. If the processor

381
00:14:18,800 --> 00:14:22,320
supports it, the dispatcher is also

382
00:14:20,639 --> 00:14:25,040
responsible for switching to user mode

383
00:14:22,320 --> 00:14:27,040
before handing control to the process.

384
00:14:25,040 --> 00:14:29,839
In other words, the scheduler determines

385
00:14:27,040 --> 00:14:31,519
which process should use the CPU next by

386
00:14:29,839 --> 00:14:33,519
managing the ready Q according to a

387
00:14:31,519 --> 00:14:35,120
specific scheduling policy while the

388
00:14:33,519 --> 00:14:37,399
dispatcher is responsible for the

389
00:14:35,120 --> 00:14:40,160
execution of the decision made by

390
00:14:37,399 --> 00:14:42,160
theuler. These additional CPU bursts

391
00:14:40,160 --> 00:14:44,320
caused by the dispatcher are inevitable

392
00:14:42,160 --> 00:14:46,959
since the CPU itself is required to

393
00:14:44,320 --> 00:14:49,279
execute the context switch. This delay

394
00:14:46,959 --> 00:14:50,959
is known as dispatch latency, the time

395
00:14:49,279 --> 00:14:53,440
it takes for the dispatcher to stop one

396
00:14:50,959 --> 00:14:55,199
process and start another. Because the

397
00:14:53,440 --> 00:14:57,639
dispatcher is invoked during every

398
00:14:55,199 --> 00:14:59,839
context switch, it must be as fast as

399
00:14:57,639 --> 00:15:01,519
possible. For this reason, the

400
00:14:59,839 --> 00:15:03,279
dispatcher is one of the most highly

401
00:15:01,519 --> 00:15:05,680
optimized components of an operating

402
00:15:03,279 --> 00:15:07,519
system. Since it is implicit, the

403
00:15:05,680 --> 00:15:09,079
dispatch latency is usually not

404
00:15:07,519 --> 00:15:11,920
illustrated between

405
00:15:09,079 --> 00:15:14,320
processes. By the way, this is a variant

406
00:15:11,920 --> 00:15:16,079
of something known as a Gant chart, a

407
00:15:14,320 --> 00:15:18,320
bar chart that illustrates a specific

408
00:15:16,079 --> 00:15:20,360
schedule showing the start and finish

409
00:15:18,320 --> 00:15:22,959
times of each participating

410
00:15:20,360 --> 00:15:25,040
process. In first come firsts served

411
00:15:22,959 --> 00:15:28,399
scheduling. This policy is implemented

412
00:15:25,040 --> 00:15:30,800
using a FIFO Q as the ready Q. As soon

413
00:15:28,399 --> 00:15:32,800
as a process makes an IO request, the

414
00:15:30,800 --> 00:15:35,160
CPU is immediately allocated to the

415
00:15:32,800 --> 00:15:38,000
process at the head of the

416
00:15:35,160 --> 00:15:39,839
queue. Notice that the name first come

417
00:15:38,000 --> 00:15:41,519
first served can be somewhat ambiguous

418
00:15:39,839 --> 00:15:44,000
because the scheduler is not actually

419
00:15:41,519 --> 00:15:46,959
managing entire processes but rather

420
00:15:44,000 --> 00:15:49,600
their next CPU burst. A more precise

421
00:15:46,959 --> 00:15:51,279
name would be first CPU burst come first

422
00:15:49,600 --> 00:15:53,199
served.

423
00:15:51,279 --> 00:15:54,959
That said, since many books and

424
00:15:53,199 --> 00:15:57,040
resources continue to refer to it as

425
00:15:54,959 --> 00:15:59,839
first come, first served, we'll stick

426
00:15:57,040 --> 00:16:02,120
with that convention. And with that, we

427
00:15:59,839 --> 00:16:04,720
have the simplest CPU scheduling

428
00:16:02,120 --> 00:16:06,639
algorithm. But while it does take CPU

429
00:16:04,720 --> 00:16:09,360
utilization into account, that doesn't

430
00:16:06,639 --> 00:16:11,600
mean it's effective at optimizing it. To

431
00:16:09,360 --> 00:16:14,320
understand why, let's go back to our CPU

432
00:16:11,600 --> 00:16:16,800
burst frequency graph. Notice that while

433
00:16:14,320 --> 00:16:19,360
very large CPU bursts are rare, their

434
00:16:16,800 --> 00:16:21,600
probability is never zero.

435
00:16:19,360 --> 00:16:23,920
The most common processes, those with a

436
00:16:21,600 --> 00:16:26,800
high number of short CPU bursts, are

437
00:16:23,920 --> 00:16:28,639
known as IObound processes. These

438
00:16:26,800 --> 00:16:30,560
processes depend heavily on IO

439
00:16:28,639 --> 00:16:34,279
operations, meaning their performance

440
00:16:30,560 --> 00:16:36,720
would improve if the IO subsystem were

441
00:16:34,279 --> 00:16:38,560
faster. But it is also possible to have

442
00:16:36,720 --> 00:16:41,839
processes that exhibit a high number of

443
00:16:38,560 --> 00:16:43,920
long CPU bursts. Unlike IObound

444
00:16:41,839 --> 00:16:46,160
processes, these processes do not

445
00:16:43,920 --> 00:16:48,720
benefit significantly from a faster IO

446
00:16:46,160 --> 00:16:51,839
subsystem, but instead they depend on

447
00:16:48,720 --> 00:16:54,959
faster CPU speeds and for that reason

448
00:16:51,839 --> 00:16:56,880
these are called CPUbound processes. The

449
00:16:54,959 --> 00:16:58,560
problem with CPUbounded processes and

450
00:16:56,880 --> 00:17:00,639
the first come first serve scheduling

451
00:16:58,560 --> 00:17:03,480
algorithm is that they can generate a

452
00:17:00,639 --> 00:17:05,360
negative effect on CPU

453
00:17:03,480 --> 00:17:07,720
utilization. Imagine we have one

454
00:17:05,360 --> 00:17:09,919
CPUbound process and some IObound

455
00:17:07,720 --> 00:17:12,600
processes. For convenience, I'm going to

456
00:17:09,919 --> 00:17:15,439
use the same color for the IO bound

457
00:17:12,600 --> 00:17:17,520
processes. The CPUbound process will get

458
00:17:15,439 --> 00:17:20,079
and hold the CPU for a relatively long

459
00:17:17,520 --> 00:17:22,240
time. During this time, all the other

460
00:17:20,079 --> 00:17:24,439
processes will finish their IO and will

461
00:17:22,240 --> 00:17:26,799
move into the ready Q, waiting for the

462
00:17:24,439 --> 00:17:29,760
CPU. While the processes wait in the

463
00:17:26,799 --> 00:17:31,840
ready Q, the IO devices are idle.

464
00:17:29,760 --> 00:17:34,000
Eventually, the CPUbound process

465
00:17:31,840 --> 00:17:36,960
finishes its CPU burst and moves to an

466
00:17:34,000 --> 00:17:39,360
IO device. All the IObound processes

467
00:17:36,960 --> 00:17:42,160
which have short CPU bursts execute

468
00:17:39,360 --> 00:17:44,000
quickly and move back to the IOQ cues.

469
00:17:42,160 --> 00:17:46,400
At this point, there's no process to

470
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:48,480
dispatch and the CPU sits idle. The

471
00:17:46,400 --> 00:17:51,440
CPUbound process will then move back to

472
00:17:48,480 --> 00:17:53,760
the ready Q and be allocated the CPU

473
00:17:51,440 --> 00:17:55,280
again. All the IO processes end up

474
00:17:53,760 --> 00:17:58,720
waiting in the ready Q until the

475
00:17:55,280 --> 00:17:58,720
CPUbound process is

476
00:17:59,080 --> 00:18:04,960
done. See the problem here? There is a

477
00:18:02,640 --> 00:18:06,720
convoy effect as all the other processes

478
00:18:04,960 --> 00:18:09,360
wait for the one big process to get off

479
00:18:06,720 --> 00:18:11,919
the CPU. This effect results in lower

480
00:18:09,360 --> 00:18:13,679
CPU and device utilization than might be

481
00:18:11,919 --> 00:18:15,080
possible if the shorter processes were

482
00:18:13,679 --> 00:18:17,760
allowed to go

483
00:18:15,080 --> 00:18:19,840
first. Yes, the shorted job first

484
00:18:17,760 --> 00:18:22,799
scheduling algorithm exists and is the

485
00:18:19,840 --> 00:18:22,799
next one we are going to

486
00:18:24,679 --> 00:18:29,360
learn. Shortest job first assigns the

487
00:18:27,440 --> 00:18:32,240
CPU to the process with the shortest

488
00:18:29,360 --> 00:18:34,400
next CPU burst. If two processes have

489
00:18:32,240 --> 00:18:36,520
the same burst length, first come first

490
00:18:34,400 --> 00:18:38,880
served is used as a

491
00:18:36,520 --> 00:18:41,200
tiebreaker. Again, note that a more

492
00:18:38,880 --> 00:18:43,280
precise name would be shortest next CPU

493
00:18:41,200 --> 00:18:45,600
burst first scheduling since it

494
00:18:43,280 --> 00:18:48,240
prioritizes the next CPU burst rather

495
00:18:45,600 --> 00:18:50,160
than the total process length. Most

496
00:18:48,240 --> 00:18:52,320
people in books refer to it as shortest

497
00:18:50,160 --> 00:18:54,080
job first. So once again, let's stick to

498
00:18:52,320 --> 00:18:55,840
that convention.

499
00:18:54,080 --> 00:18:58,000
This algorithm can be implemented using

500
00:18:55,840 --> 00:19:00,160
a priority queue where priority is

501
00:18:58,000 --> 00:19:02,559
determined by the length of the next CPU

502
00:19:00,160 --> 00:19:04,720
burst of the waiting processes. This

503
00:19:02,559 --> 00:19:07,200
allows those short CPU burst processes

504
00:19:04,720 --> 00:19:09,600
to overtake those CPU hungry processes

505
00:19:07,200 --> 00:19:11,840
reducing the convoy effect. This

506
00:19:09,600 --> 00:19:13,120
algorithm is also provably optimal in

507
00:19:11,840 --> 00:19:15,320
that it gives the minimum average

508
00:19:13,120 --> 00:19:17,280
waiting time for a given set of

509
00:19:15,320 --> 00:19:18,720
processes. Imagine we have four

510
00:19:17,280 --> 00:19:21,280
processes that arrive almost

511
00:19:18,720 --> 00:19:23,760
simultaneously. The first process next

512
00:19:21,280 --> 00:19:25,120
CPU burst takes 2 minutes to complete

513
00:19:23,760 --> 00:19:28,080
while the others only take a few

514
00:19:25,120 --> 00:19:30,160
milliseconds each. In first come first

515
00:19:28,080 --> 00:19:32,320
serve. If those shorter CPU bursts

516
00:19:30,160 --> 00:19:34,000
arrive just after the long CPU burst,

517
00:19:32,320 --> 00:19:35,280
they would experience significant delays

518
00:19:34,000 --> 00:19:36,600
because they'd have to wait for the

519
00:19:35,280 --> 00:19:39,360
longer to

520
00:19:36,600 --> 00:19:41,520
finish. On the other hand, if processes

521
00:19:39,360 --> 00:19:43,280
with short CPU burst are allowed to go

522
00:19:41,520 --> 00:19:45,280
first, their waiting times would be

523
00:19:43,280 --> 00:19:47,919
minimal and the process with the longer

524
00:19:45,280 --> 00:19:49,440
CPU burst would barely be affected. it

525
00:19:47,919 --> 00:19:50,960
would simply start a few milliseconds

526
00:19:49,440 --> 00:19:53,760
later, which would make little

527
00:19:50,960 --> 00:19:55,760
difference to it. Moving a short process

528
00:19:53,760 --> 00:19:57,919
before a long one decreases the waiting

529
00:19:55,760 --> 00:19:59,880
time of the short process more than it

530
00:19:57,919 --> 00:20:02,400
increases the waiting time of the long

531
00:19:59,880 --> 00:20:03,880
process. Consequently, the average

532
00:20:02,400 --> 00:20:06,080
waiting time

533
00:20:03,880 --> 00:20:08,160
decreases. Minimizing the average

534
00:20:06,080 --> 00:20:09,840
waiting time in a system is crucial

535
00:20:08,160 --> 00:20:12,080
because it represents the time that

536
00:20:09,840 --> 00:20:13,919
processes are ready to run but cannot

537
00:20:12,080 --> 00:20:17,120
execute as they wait for their turn to

538
00:20:13,919 --> 00:20:18,799
use the CPU.

539
00:20:17,120 --> 00:20:20,799
There are important considerations to

540
00:20:18,799 --> 00:20:23,679
keep in mind whenever auler relies on

541
00:20:20,799 --> 00:20:25,760
priority cues as we'll explore later.

542
00:20:23,679 --> 00:20:28,159
But there's one major issue specifically

543
00:20:25,760 --> 00:20:29,880
tied to shortest jobs first. It is

544
00:20:28,159 --> 00:20:32,000
impossible to implement

545
00:20:29,880 --> 00:20:33,840
perfectly because unless we could see

546
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:36,159
the future, there is no way to know the

547
00:20:33,840 --> 00:20:38,480
exact length of a process's next CPU

548
00:20:36,159 --> 00:20:39,919
burst.

549
00:20:38,480 --> 00:20:41,520
You might think that we could use the

550
00:20:39,919 --> 00:20:43,760
program counter to determine where the

551
00:20:41,520 --> 00:20:45,840
next system call occurs and how long the

552
00:20:43,760 --> 00:20:48,559
process will use the CPU before its next

553
00:20:45,840 --> 00:20:50,559
IO burst. However, this approach is

554
00:20:48,559 --> 00:20:52,559
unreliable because between the current

555
00:20:50,559 --> 00:20:54,159
instruction and the next system call,

556
00:20:52,559 --> 00:20:57,039
there can be loops or function calls

557
00:20:54,159 --> 00:20:59,120
that alter execution time. The program's

558
00:20:57,039 --> 00:21:01,679
execution path may depend on external

559
00:20:59,120 --> 00:21:04,240
inputs like the user input, making

560
00:21:01,679 --> 00:21:06,240
prediction even harder. For example,

561
00:21:04,240 --> 00:21:08,159
this function takes an user input,

562
00:21:06,240 --> 00:21:10,480
convert it to uppercase, and then print

563
00:21:08,159 --> 00:21:12,360
it. The amount of iterations depends on

564
00:21:10,480 --> 00:21:14,880
the length of the user

565
00:21:12,360 --> 00:21:17,440
input. Since we cannot know the exact

566
00:21:14,880 --> 00:21:20,080
next CPU burst, the best we can do is

567
00:21:17,440 --> 00:21:21,840
estimate it based on past CPU bursts

568
00:21:20,080 --> 00:21:23,600
with the assumption that the next CPU

569
00:21:21,840 --> 00:21:26,159
burst will likely be similar in length

570
00:21:23,600 --> 00:21:28,240
to previous ones. To approximate this

571
00:21:26,159 --> 00:21:29,840
value, we compute an estimate using an

572
00:21:28,240 --> 00:21:32,240
exponential average of previously

573
00:21:29,840 --> 00:21:34,159
measured CPU bursts.

574
00:21:32,240 --> 00:21:36,679
I know this isn't rocket science, but if

575
00:21:34,159 --> 00:21:38,880
you're not into math, I'll break it

576
00:21:36,679 --> 00:21:41,120
down. First, it's important to

577
00:21:38,880 --> 00:21:42,880
understand that each process's CPU burst

578
00:21:41,120 --> 00:21:45,280
prediction depends only on its own

579
00:21:42,880 --> 00:21:47,919
history. Other processes do not affect

580
00:21:45,280 --> 00:21:49,760
its prediction. Each process's CPU

581
00:21:47,919 --> 00:21:51,240
bursts form a sequence of observed

582
00:21:49,760 --> 00:21:54,880
durations over

583
00:21:51,240 --> 00:21:57,679
time. N is the most recent CPU burst. N

584
00:21:54,880 --> 00:21:59,840
minus one is the previous CPU burst. N

585
00:21:57,679 --> 00:22:03,440
minus2 is the one before that, and so

586
00:21:59,840 --> 00:22:06,159
on. n +1 is the next CPU burst, the one

587
00:22:03,440 --> 00:22:08,320
we want to predict in the formula. That

588
00:22:06,159 --> 00:22:10,120
means toao subn is the predicted burst

589
00:22:08,320 --> 00:22:12,799
time for the process in the most recent

590
00:22:10,120 --> 00:22:16,080
iteration while t subn is the actual

591
00:22:12,799 --> 00:22:18,400
burst time that was observed. So to subn

592
00:22:16,080 --> 00:22:20,880
+ 1 is the estimated CPU burst duration

593
00:22:18,400 --> 00:22:20,880
for the next

594
00:22:21,960 --> 00:22:26,640
iteration. Since to subn represents the

595
00:22:24,799 --> 00:22:27,799
previous prediction, we can expand the

596
00:22:26,640 --> 00:22:30,640
formula

597
00:22:27,799 --> 00:22:32,559
recursively. Since to subn minus one is

598
00:22:30,640 --> 00:22:34,760
the prediction before that we can expand

599
00:22:32,559 --> 00:22:40,559
it

600
00:22:34,760 --> 00:22:40,559
again and then with subn minus2 and so

601
00:22:42,520 --> 00:22:47,919
on. What this shows is that this term

602
00:22:45,120 --> 00:22:49,679
retains the process's past history. As a

603
00:22:47,919 --> 00:22:51,840
result, we don't need to store an entire

604
00:22:49,679 --> 00:22:54,080
list of possibly thousands of CPU burst

605
00:22:51,840 --> 00:22:56,320
durations. We only need to keep the most

606
00:22:54,080 --> 00:22:56,320
recent

607
00:22:57,480 --> 00:23:01,679
prediction. And what about this

608
00:22:59,200 --> 00:23:01,679
parameter

609
00:23:01,880 --> 00:23:07,280
alpha? Well, if alpha equals zero, the

610
00:23:05,440 --> 00:23:09,200
most recent CPU burst is completely

611
00:23:07,280 --> 00:23:12,760
ignored and the prediction relies only

612
00:23:09,200 --> 00:23:12,760
on past history.

613
00:23:15,919 --> 00:23:20,880
If alpha equals 1, the prediction is

614
00:23:18,240 --> 00:23:23,000
based only on the most recent CPU burst,

615
00:23:20,880 --> 00:23:25,520
ignoring all past

616
00:23:23,000 --> 00:23:27,039
history. Thus, alpha controls the

617
00:23:25,520 --> 00:23:29,840
relative weight of the recent and the

618
00:23:27,039 --> 00:23:32,400
past history in our prediction. A common

619
00:23:29,840 --> 00:23:35,000
choice is alpha equals 1/2 which gives

620
00:23:32,400 --> 00:23:37,120
equal weight to recent and past

621
00:23:35,000 --> 00:23:39,120
history. And notice that this doesn't

622
00:23:37,120 --> 00:23:41,679
mean all observed CPU burst in the

623
00:23:39,120 --> 00:23:43,600
history are equally weighted. By

624
00:23:41,679 --> 00:23:46,000
expanding the formula, we can see that

625
00:23:43,600 --> 00:23:49,200
each CPU burst duration is multiplied by

626
00:23:46,000 --> 00:23:51,919
alpha * 1 - alpha raised to a power.

627
00:23:49,200 --> 00:23:54,480
Since alpha is between 0 and 1, the term

628
00:23:51,919 --> 00:23:56,400
1 - alpha decreases exponentially,

629
00:23:54,480 --> 00:23:58,039
meaning older CPU bursts have less

630
00:23:56,400 --> 00:24:00,080
influence on the

631
00:23:58,039 --> 00:24:01,760
prediction. This makes sense because

632
00:24:00,080 --> 00:24:03,720
older execution patterns are less

633
00:24:01,760 --> 00:24:06,480
relevant when predicting future CPU

634
00:24:03,720 --> 00:24:08,640
bursts. Additionally, when a process is

635
00:24:06,480 --> 00:24:11,360
first created, there is no historical

636
00:24:08,640 --> 00:24:12,880
data. In this case, the initial

637
00:24:11,360 --> 00:24:14,799
prediction is typically set to a

638
00:24:12,880 --> 00:24:16,799
constant value defined by the operating

639
00:24:14,799 --> 00:24:19,279
system or based on the systemwide

640
00:24:16,799 --> 00:24:21,520
average. For example, using a starting

641
00:24:19,279 --> 00:24:24,279
value of 100 milliseconds results in a

642
00:24:21,520 --> 00:24:26,880
predicted next CPU burst of around 72

643
00:24:24,279 --> 00:24:28,960
milliseconds, which as you can see is

644
00:24:26,880 --> 00:24:30,279
closer to recent CPU bursts than the

645
00:24:28,960 --> 00:24:32,559
oldest

646
00:24:30,279 --> 00:24:34,720
ones. Here's a chart comparing the

647
00:24:32,559 --> 00:24:37,440
predicted versus observed CPU bursts

648
00:24:34,720 --> 00:24:40,279
over a longer period of time. While not

649
00:24:37,440 --> 00:24:42,159
perfect, this approach provides a decent

650
00:24:40,279 --> 00:24:43,840
approximation. But there's an important

651
00:24:42,159 --> 00:24:46,080
decision the dispatcher must make that

652
00:24:43,840 --> 00:24:48,080
we haven't discussed yet. Imagine

653
00:24:46,080 --> 00:24:50,000
process A enters the ready Q with a

654
00:24:48,080 --> 00:24:52,320
specific next CPU burst and is

655
00:24:50,000 --> 00:24:54,400
eventually allowed to run. Then an

656
00:24:52,320 --> 00:24:57,600
instant later, process B enters the

657
00:24:54,400 --> 00:24:59,760
ready Q, but process A is still running.

658
00:24:57,600 --> 00:25:01,679
The question is if the remaining CPU

659
00:24:59,760 --> 00:25:04,240
burst of process A is longer than the

660
00:25:01,679 --> 00:25:05,840
next CPU burst of process B, should

661
00:25:04,240 --> 00:25:08,880
process A be interrupted to give

662
00:25:05,840 --> 00:25:11,520
priority to process B? This decision

663
00:25:08,880 --> 00:25:13,520
depends on theuler. If auler allows

664
00:25:11,520 --> 00:25:15,200
running processes to be interrupted, we

665
00:25:13,520 --> 00:25:17,120
are dealing with a preemptive scheduling

666
00:25:15,200 --> 00:25:20,240
algorithm where the operating system can

667
00:25:17,120 --> 00:25:23,039
preempt currently executing processes.

668
00:25:20,240 --> 00:25:25,279
In contrast, a non-premptive will never

669
00:25:23,039 --> 00:25:27,520
preempt a running process. Even if a

670
00:25:25,279 --> 00:25:29,440
process with a shorter CPU burst arrives

671
00:25:27,520 --> 00:25:31,120
in the ready queue, it will have to wait

672
00:25:29,440 --> 00:25:33,480
until the running process completes its

673
00:25:31,120 --> 00:25:36,320
CPU burst and releases the

674
00:25:33,480 --> 00:25:38,159
CPU. This is not a trivial decision as

675
00:25:36,320 --> 00:25:39,760
the execution order of processes can

676
00:25:38,159 --> 00:25:43,000
change depending on whether the shortest

677
00:25:39,760 --> 00:25:44,799
job first algorithm is preemptive or

678
00:25:43,000 --> 00:25:46,720
non-premptive. And now that we

679
00:25:44,799 --> 00:25:48,640
understand preeemption, let's discuss

680
00:25:46,720 --> 00:25:50,200
why it is the default choice in modern

681
00:25:48,640 --> 00:25:52,960
systems.

682
00:25:50,200 --> 00:25:55,120
Consider a non-premptive system where a

683
00:25:52,960 --> 00:25:57,039
process with an extremely long next CPU

684
00:25:55,120 --> 00:25:59,600
burst reaches the head of the ready Q

685
00:25:57,039 --> 00:26:01,360
and is selected. Since the system is

686
00:25:59,600 --> 00:26:02,799
non-premptive, there is no way to

687
00:26:01,360 --> 00:26:05,960
interrupt this process until it

688
00:26:02,799 --> 00:26:09,559
voluntarily releases the

689
00:26:05,960 --> 00:26:12,240
CPU. But what if it never

690
00:26:09,559 --> 00:26:14,559
does? Infinite loops are not uncommon in

691
00:26:12,240 --> 00:26:16,559
computer science. If no system call is

692
00:26:14,559 --> 00:26:18,400
used inside the loop, the process will

693
00:26:16,559 --> 00:26:19,520
never return control of the CPU to the

694
00:26:18,400 --> 00:26:21,360
OS.

695
00:26:19,520 --> 00:26:24,360
This is problematic in general purpose

696
00:26:21,360 --> 00:26:27,039
systems where concurrency is a key

697
00:26:24,360 --> 00:26:28,640
feature. Remember, concurrency is a

698
00:26:27,039 --> 00:26:30,640
technique that allows the CPU to

699
00:26:28,640 --> 00:26:32,720
alternate execution between processes

700
00:26:30,640 --> 00:26:34,200
very quickly, creating the illusion that

701
00:26:32,720 --> 00:26:36,000
all processes are running

702
00:26:34,200 --> 00:26:38,640
simultaneously. However, in

703
00:26:36,000 --> 00:26:41,039
non-premptive systems, if a CPUbound

704
00:26:38,640 --> 00:26:43,120
process holds the CPU indefinitely or

705
00:26:41,039 --> 00:26:44,880
even for long periods, all other

706
00:26:43,120 --> 00:26:46,720
processes freeze from the user's

707
00:26:44,880 --> 00:26:48,720
perspective. This is a major issue

708
00:26:46,720 --> 00:26:50,960
because non-premptive systems rely on

709
00:26:48,720 --> 00:26:53,440
processes to behave correctly and return

710
00:26:50,960 --> 00:26:54,799
control in a reasonable amount of time.

711
00:26:53,440 --> 00:26:56,559
Malware could exploit this by

712
00:26:54,799 --> 00:26:59,279
intentionally avoiding system calls to

713
00:26:56,559 --> 00:27:01,039
monopolize CPU time. Whenever a

714
00:26:59,279 --> 00:27:03,120
scheduling policy causes a process to

715
00:27:01,039 --> 00:27:05,200
wait indefinitely in the ready queue,

716
00:27:03,120 --> 00:27:07,640
this is called starvation because the

717
00:27:05,200 --> 00:27:10,799
process is starving for CPU

718
00:27:07,640 --> 00:27:12,960
time. Even CPUbound processes can suffer

719
00:27:10,799 --> 00:27:15,200
from starvation. For example, in

720
00:27:12,960 --> 00:27:17,600
shortest job first, a process with a

721
00:27:15,200 --> 00:27:19,440
long estimated CPU burst may be forced

722
00:27:17,600 --> 00:27:21,400
to stay in the queue indefinitely if

723
00:27:19,440 --> 00:27:23,600
many shorter CPU bursts continue

724
00:27:21,400 --> 00:27:26,320
arriving. The only way for this process

725
00:27:23,600 --> 00:27:28,880
to get CPU time is if no other process

726
00:27:26,320 --> 00:27:31,279
is in the ready queue. In real world

727
00:27:28,880 --> 00:27:35,039
systems, this is unlikely since hundreds

728
00:27:31,279 --> 00:27:35,039
of processes compete for CPU

729
00:27:35,240 --> 00:27:40,159
time. In terms of concurrency, that

730
00:27:37,679 --> 00:27:41,919
would look something like this. Thus,

731
00:27:40,159 --> 00:27:43,919
starvation is not just about process

732
00:27:41,919 --> 00:27:46,720
burst length, but rather a consequence

733
00:27:43,919 --> 00:27:48,559
of the scheduling policy itself. While

734
00:27:46,720 --> 00:27:51,120
shortest job first is efficient in terms

735
00:27:48,559 --> 00:27:52,559
of CPU utilization and waiting time, a

736
00:27:51,120 --> 00:27:56,559
general purpose operating system

737
00:27:52,559 --> 00:27:56,559
requires other scheduling criteria as

738
00:27:58,039 --> 00:28:02,679
well. A great example of preemptive

739
00:28:00,640 --> 00:28:05,039
scheduling is the roundroin

740
00:28:02,679 --> 00:28:06,559
algorithm. The roundrobin scheduling

741
00:28:05,039 --> 00:28:09,039
algorithm is similar to first come

742
00:28:06,559 --> 00:28:10,720
first-s serve scheduling. A FIFO Q is

743
00:28:09,039 --> 00:28:12,320
used as a ready Q, but preeemption is

744
00:28:10,720 --> 00:28:15,279
added to enable the system to switch

745
00:28:12,320 --> 00:28:17,440
between processes. A small unit of time

746
00:28:15,279 --> 00:28:19,440
called a time quantum or time slice is

747
00:28:17,440 --> 00:28:22,279
defined. Here in this animation, I'm

748
00:28:19,440 --> 00:28:24,720
using a time quantum of 100

749
00:28:22,279 --> 00:28:27,679
milliseconds. New processes are added to

750
00:28:24,720 --> 00:28:29,360
the tail of the ready Q. The CPUuler

751
00:28:27,679 --> 00:28:31,440
picks the first process from the ready

752
00:28:29,360 --> 00:28:33,440
Q, sets a timer to interrupt after

753
00:28:31,440 --> 00:28:35,360
one-time quantum, and dispatches the

754
00:28:33,440 --> 00:28:38,159
process. One of two things will then

755
00:28:35,360 --> 00:28:40,640
happen. The process may have a CPU burst

756
00:28:38,159 --> 00:28:42,480
of less than one time quantum. In this

757
00:28:40,640 --> 00:28:45,440
case, the process itself will release

758
00:28:42,480 --> 00:28:47,200
the CPU voluntarily. Theuler will then

759
00:28:45,440 --> 00:28:49,600
proceed to the next process in the ready

760
00:28:47,200 --> 00:28:51,440
Q. If the CPU burst of the currently

761
00:28:49,600 --> 00:28:53,520
running process is longer than one-time

762
00:28:51,440 --> 00:28:55,159
quantum, the timer will go off and will

763
00:28:53,520 --> 00:28:57,679
cause an interrupt to the operating

764
00:28:55,159 --> 00:28:59,760
system, forcing a context switch to be

765
00:28:57,679 --> 00:29:02,720
executed and the process will be put at

766
00:28:59,760 --> 00:29:04,399
the tail of the ready Q.

767
00:29:02,720 --> 00:29:07,039
The dispatcher then selects the next

768
00:29:04,399 --> 00:29:08,559
process in the ready queue. This routine

769
00:29:07,039 --> 00:29:10,880
is applied consistently to every

770
00:29:08,559 --> 00:29:13,200
dispatched process, ensuring that no

771
00:29:10,880 --> 00:29:15,360
single process can hold onto the CPU for

772
00:29:13,200 --> 00:29:17,039
long periods or indefinitely, which

773
00:29:15,360 --> 00:29:19,919
prevents other processes from being

774
00:29:17,039 --> 00:29:21,440
starved of CPU time. Something very

775
00:29:19,919 --> 00:29:23,679
important to mention is that the timer

776
00:29:21,440 --> 00:29:26,080
is a physical device, usually embedded

777
00:29:23,679 --> 00:29:27,679
in the CPU circuitry, meaning preemptive

778
00:29:26,080 --> 00:29:29,840
scheduling can only be implemented if

779
00:29:27,679 --> 00:29:31,520
the hardware provides support for it.

780
00:29:29,840 --> 00:29:32,960
There's a very cool video about this on

781
00:29:31,520 --> 00:29:35,640
the channel. So, if you want to learn

782
00:29:32,960 --> 00:29:38,080
more about the topic, go check it

783
00:29:35,640 --> 00:29:40,159
out. Notice that when a process is

784
00:29:38,080 --> 00:29:42,960
preempted, it does not enter the waiting

785
00:29:40,159 --> 00:29:45,279
state since it did not request I/IO.

786
00:29:42,960 --> 00:29:48,360
Instead, it goes directly into the ready

787
00:29:45,279 --> 00:29:50,720
state waiting for its next time

788
00:29:48,360 --> 00:29:52,799
quantum. If we need a scheduling policy

789
00:29:50,720 --> 00:29:55,279
that fairly distributes CPU time,

790
00:29:52,799 --> 00:29:56,880
roundroin is ideal. If there are n

791
00:29:55,279 --> 00:29:59,600
processes in the queue and the time

792
00:29:56,880 --> 00:30:01,760
quantum is q, each process receive one n

793
00:29:59,600 --> 00:30:02,520
of the CPU time in chunks of at most q

794
00:30:01,760 --> 00:30:05,039
time

795
00:30:02,520 --> 00:30:06,880
units. This ensures that once a process

796
00:30:05,039 --> 00:30:09,360
enters the ready queue, it will wait at

797
00:30:06,880 --> 00:30:12,399
most n minus one q time units before its

798
00:30:09,360 --> 00:30:14,880
next turn. But while roundroin ensures

799
00:30:12,399 --> 00:30:17,440
fair distribution, waiting time is not

800
00:30:14,880 --> 00:30:19,520
always optimal. If the time quantum is

801
00:30:17,440 --> 00:30:22,000
too large, most processes will enter an

802
00:30:19,520 --> 00:30:23,840
IO burst before being preempted, causing

803
00:30:22,000 --> 00:30:26,080
roundroin to behave like first come

804
00:30:23,840 --> 00:30:26,080
first

805
00:30:32,279 --> 00:30:36,640
served. At first, it might seem like the

806
00:30:34,720 --> 00:30:38,799
obvious solution is to simply reduce the

807
00:30:36,640 --> 00:30:40,960
time quantum, but if the time quantum is

808
00:30:38,799 --> 00:30:43,039
too small, processes will be interrupted

809
00:30:40,960 --> 00:30:46,520
too frequently, causing a high number of

810
00:30:43,039 --> 00:30:46,520
context switches.

811
00:30:46,799 --> 00:30:51,600
And remember context switch time is pure

812
00:30:49,520 --> 00:30:54,159
overhead because the system does no

813
00:30:51,600 --> 00:30:56,159
useful work while switching. As a

814
00:30:54,159 --> 00:30:58,640
result, processes will take longer to

815
00:30:56,159 --> 00:31:00,559
complete due to excessive interruptions.

816
00:30:58,640 --> 00:31:02,159
The CPU will spend more time switching

817
00:31:00,559 --> 00:31:03,640
between processes than actually

818
00:31:02,159 --> 00:31:06,000
executing

819
00:31:03,640 --> 00:31:08,240
them. And here we need to start talking

820
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:10,399
about another scheduling criteria. The

821
00:31:08,240 --> 00:31:12,799
turnaround time defined as the total

822
00:31:10,399 --> 00:31:14,679
time taken from a process's creation to

823
00:31:12,799 --> 00:31:16,640
its completion.

824
00:31:14,679 --> 00:31:18,640
Mathematically, it is the sum of the

825
00:31:16,640 --> 00:31:20,880
time spent waiting in the ready queue,

826
00:31:18,640 --> 00:31:23,080
the time spent executing on the CPU, and

827
00:31:20,880 --> 00:31:25,440
the time spent doing IO

828
00:31:23,080 --> 00:31:28,000
operations. Another useful metric used

829
00:31:25,440 --> 00:31:29,760
as scheduling criteria is the throughput

830
00:31:28,000 --> 00:31:31,399
defined as the number of processes that

831
00:31:29,760 --> 00:31:34,559
are completed per time

832
00:31:31,399 --> 00:31:36,480
unit. Again, if the time quantum is

833
00:31:34,559 --> 00:31:38,880
smaller than the average context switch

834
00:31:36,480 --> 00:31:40,799
time, the CPU will be busy but

835
00:31:38,880 --> 00:31:43,519
constantly switching between processes

836
00:31:40,799 --> 00:31:45,679
rather than executing them. Maximizing

837
00:31:43,519 --> 00:31:48,399
CPU utilization is meaningless if the

838
00:31:45,679 --> 00:31:50,320
CPU is not doing useful work. A

839
00:31:48,399 --> 00:31:53,039
well-designed scheduling algorithm must

840
00:31:50,320 --> 00:31:55,880
balance CPU allocation and overhead to

841
00:31:53,039 --> 00:31:58,080
optimize both turnaround time and

842
00:31:55,880 --> 00:31:59,600
throughput. The average turnaround time

843
00:31:58,080 --> 00:32:01,679
of a set of processes does not

844
00:31:59,600 --> 00:32:04,399
necessarily improve as the time quantum

845
00:32:01,679 --> 00:32:06,320
increases. Though as you can see here,

846
00:32:04,399 --> 00:32:08,399
in general, the average turnaround time

847
00:32:06,320 --> 00:32:10,559
can be improved if most processes finish

848
00:32:08,399 --> 00:32:12,559
their next CPU burst in a single time

849
00:32:10,559 --> 00:32:15,080
quantum to ensure context switches

850
00:32:12,559 --> 00:32:17,600
happen only when

851
00:32:15,080 --> 00:32:19,120
necessary. However, turnaround time is

852
00:32:17,600 --> 00:32:21,840
not always the best criterion for

853
00:32:19,120 --> 00:32:23,519
measuring scheduling efficacy. Often, a

854
00:32:21,840 --> 00:32:25,919
process can start producing output

855
00:32:23,519 --> 00:32:28,240
before completing execution. And as we

856
00:32:25,919 --> 00:32:30,240
stated earlier, some processes may even

857
00:32:28,240 --> 00:32:32,480
never terminate.

858
00:32:30,240 --> 00:32:34,880
Thus, another important metric is the

859
00:32:32,480 --> 00:32:36,880
response time defined as the time from

860
00:32:34,880 --> 00:32:39,440
submission of a request to the first

861
00:32:36,880 --> 00:32:41,360
response produced. This is not the total

862
00:32:39,440 --> 00:32:43,360
time needed to complete execution of a

863
00:32:41,360 --> 00:32:45,840
process, but rather how quickly it

864
00:32:43,360 --> 00:32:47,279
starts responding. Response time is

865
00:32:45,840 --> 00:32:49,039
critical because it directly affects

866
00:32:47,279 --> 00:32:50,880
that smooth feeling that users expect

867
00:32:49,039 --> 00:32:53,120
from interactive systems, especially

868
00:32:50,880 --> 00:32:53,120
when

869
00:32:53,240 --> 00:32:57,679
multitasking. Roundroin is one of the

870
00:32:55,440 --> 00:32:59,600
simplest ways to achieve concurrency.

871
00:32:57,679 --> 00:33:02,159
Each process gets a fixed time quantum

872
00:32:59,600 --> 00:33:04,000
in a rotating fashion. Once a process

873
00:33:02,159 --> 00:33:06,159
finishes its time quantum, the next

874
00:33:04,000 --> 00:33:08,240
process is allowed to run. If this

875
00:33:06,159 --> 00:33:10,919
rotation happens fast enough, the system

876
00:33:08,240 --> 00:33:12,960
appears to be executing all processes

877
00:33:10,919 --> 00:33:14,640
simultaneously. The only problem is that

878
00:33:12,960 --> 00:33:16,559
all computer processors have a speed

879
00:33:14,640 --> 00:33:18,559
limit. As the number of concurrent

880
00:33:16,559 --> 00:33:20,880
processes increases, round robin

881
00:33:18,559 --> 00:33:22,880
struggles to maintain responsiveness. At

882
00:33:20,880 --> 00:33:24,880
some point, the number of processes will

883
00:33:22,880 --> 00:33:27,600
be so high that each process will wait

884
00:33:24,880 --> 00:33:29,760
much longer before getting CPU time. and

885
00:33:27,600 --> 00:33:33,000
the illusion of simultaneous execution

886
00:33:29,760 --> 00:33:35,360
breaks down as the average response time

887
00:33:33,000 --> 00:33:37,760
increases. Decreasing the time quantum

888
00:33:35,360 --> 00:33:39,440
might seem like a solution. After all,

889
00:33:37,760 --> 00:33:42,320
it could make it look like processes

890
00:33:39,440 --> 00:33:44,159
regain CPU time more frequently. But as

891
00:33:42,320 --> 00:33:46,240
we've already discussed, reducing the

892
00:33:44,159 --> 00:33:48,760
time quantum too much leads to excessive

893
00:33:46,240 --> 00:33:50,960
context switches, which is just as

894
00:33:48,760 --> 00:33:53,679
problematic. To deal with this issue,

895
00:33:50,960 --> 00:33:55,760
there are three possible solutions.

896
00:33:53,679 --> 00:33:58,080
increase the processor speed allowing

897
00:33:55,760 --> 00:33:59,760
context switches to happen faster. So we

898
00:33:58,080 --> 00:34:02,960
can use smaller time quantums without

899
00:33:59,760 --> 00:34:04,880
negatively affecting turnaround time or

900
00:34:02,960 --> 00:34:06,799
use multiple processors allowing

901
00:34:04,880 --> 00:34:09,679
processes to run in parallel and share

902
00:34:06,799 --> 00:34:11,839
the workload. However, both of these

903
00:34:09,679 --> 00:34:14,240
require hardware upgrades which are not

904
00:34:11,839 --> 00:34:15,919
always feasible. But the third solution

905
00:34:14,240 --> 00:34:17,720
can be achieved through software alone

906
00:34:15,919 --> 00:34:19,839
with a smarter

907
00:34:17,720 --> 00:34:21,919
CPUuler. Think about the processes

908
00:34:19,839 --> 00:34:23,520
running on your computer. You might be

909
00:34:21,919 --> 00:34:26,079
playing a video game while streaming

910
00:34:23,520 --> 00:34:28,240
with Outlook, a Gmail client, a file

911
00:34:26,079 --> 00:34:30,480
explorer, and other background apps all

912
00:34:28,240 --> 00:34:34,359
running simultaneously. So much stuff

913
00:34:30,480 --> 00:34:37,280
that roundroin causes your game to lag a

914
00:34:34,359 --> 00:34:38,960
bit. The question here is, do all these

915
00:34:37,280 --> 00:34:42,560
processes really need the same amount of

916
00:34:38,960 --> 00:34:44,560
CPU time? Probably not. If we assign

917
00:34:42,560 --> 00:34:46,480
higher priority to the right processes,

918
00:34:44,560 --> 00:34:48,159
we can increase their response time,

919
00:34:46,480 --> 00:34:50,720
making them feel smooth and responsive

920
00:34:48,159 --> 00:34:52,560
again from the user's perspective. Yes,

921
00:34:50,720 --> 00:34:54,879
it's true that background processes will

922
00:34:52,560 --> 00:34:57,200
get the CPU less often, but think about

923
00:34:54,879 --> 00:34:59,480
it. Does it really matter if your email

924
00:34:57,200 --> 00:35:02,240
notification is delayed by half a

925
00:34:59,480 --> 00:35:04,320
second? That said, not all background

926
00:35:02,240 --> 00:35:06,960
processes are trivial. Some, like

927
00:35:04,320 --> 00:35:09,200
operating system services, are critical.

928
00:35:06,960 --> 00:35:11,200
The key point is this. If we can

929
00:35:09,200 --> 00:35:13,280
correctly identify which processes need

930
00:35:11,200 --> 00:35:15,760
higher priority, we can significantly

931
00:35:13,280 --> 00:35:18,079
improve overall system responsiveness

932
00:35:15,760 --> 00:35:21,040
without upgrading the CPU or adding more

933
00:35:18,079 --> 00:35:21,040
cores.

934
00:35:21,280 --> 00:35:25,359
Priority scheduling is implemented using

935
00:35:23,119 --> 00:35:27,200
a priority Q where each process is

936
00:35:25,359 --> 00:35:28,520
assigned an integer value representing

937
00:35:27,200 --> 00:35:31,440
its

938
00:35:28,520 --> 00:35:33,520
priority. In this example, I'm using one

939
00:35:31,440 --> 00:35:35,839
and zero to distinguish between high and

940
00:35:33,520 --> 00:35:37,760
low priority, but the actual range of

941
00:35:35,839 --> 00:35:40,800
priority values varies depending on the

942
00:35:37,760 --> 00:35:44,000
operating system. Some systems may use a

943
00:35:40,800 --> 00:35:46,880
range from 0 to 255. Others might go

944
00:35:44,000 --> 00:35:48,960
from 0 to 32,000, especially when a

945
00:35:46,880 --> 00:35:51,359
finer granularity of priority levels is

946
00:35:48,960 --> 00:35:53,760
needed. Whether lower numbers represent

947
00:35:51,359 --> 00:35:56,079
higher or lower priority also depends on

948
00:35:53,760 --> 00:35:58,119
the system. In this animation, lower

949
00:35:56,079 --> 00:36:00,480
values indicate higher

950
00:35:58,119 --> 00:36:02,560
priority. It's also common to combine

951
00:36:00,480 --> 00:36:04,640
multiple scheduling strategies. For

952
00:36:02,560 --> 00:36:06,400
example, priority scheduling can be

953
00:36:04,640 --> 00:36:08,240
combined with roundroin to ensure

954
00:36:06,400 --> 00:36:11,240
fairness among processes with the same

955
00:36:08,240 --> 00:36:11,240
priority.

956
00:36:15,599 --> 00:36:19,680
One inherent issue with priority

957
00:36:17,280 --> 00:36:21,760
scheduling is starvation. In a heavily

958
00:36:19,680 --> 00:36:23,920
loaded system, a steady stream of higher

959
00:36:21,760 --> 00:36:26,520
priority processes can prevent a low

960
00:36:23,920 --> 00:36:29,200
priority process from ever getting the

961
00:36:26,520 --> 00:36:31,040
CPU. If this sounds familiar, that's

962
00:36:29,200 --> 00:36:32,720
because the shortest job first algorithm

963
00:36:31,040 --> 00:36:34,640
is essentially a type of priority

964
00:36:32,720 --> 00:36:37,640
scheduling where priority is based on

965
00:36:34,640 --> 00:36:41,599
the inverse of the predicted next CPU

966
00:36:37,640 --> 00:36:45,200
burst. Here's an interesting story. The

967
00:36:41,599 --> 00:36:47,440
IBM 7094, a powerful mainframe computer

968
00:36:45,200 --> 00:36:49,599
used by NASA and the US Air Force for

969
00:36:47,440 --> 00:36:50,920
scientific and military applications,

970
00:36:49,599 --> 00:36:53,280
was introduced in

971
00:36:50,920 --> 00:36:56,000
1962. Rumor has it that when they shut

972
00:36:53,280 --> 00:36:57,920
it down in 1973, they found a low

973
00:36:56,000 --> 00:37:01,480
priority process that had been submitted

974
00:36:57,920 --> 00:37:03,839
back in 1967 and had not yet been

975
00:37:01,480 --> 00:37:05,680
run. A solution to the problem of

976
00:37:03,839 --> 00:37:08,400
indefinite blockage of low priority

977
00:37:05,680 --> 00:37:10,160
processes is aging. Aging involves

978
00:37:08,400 --> 00:37:12,079
gradually increasing the priority of

979
00:37:10,160 --> 00:37:15,359
processes that wait in the system for a

980
00:37:12,079 --> 00:37:20,000
long time. For example, if priorities

981
00:37:15,359 --> 00:37:22,720
range from 127 low to zero high, we

982
00:37:20,000 --> 00:37:24,320
could periodically say every second

983
00:37:22,720 --> 00:37:27,440
increase the priority of a waiting

984
00:37:24,320 --> 00:37:30,160
process by one. Eventually, even a

985
00:37:27,440 --> 00:37:31,760
process with an initial priority of 127

986
00:37:30,160 --> 00:37:34,520
would have the highest priority in the

987
00:37:31,760 --> 00:37:36,800
system and would be

988
00:37:34,520 --> 00:37:39,280
executed with both priority and

989
00:37:36,800 --> 00:37:41,520
roundroin scheduling. All processes may

990
00:37:39,280 --> 00:37:43,280
be placed in a single queue, but

991
00:37:41,520 --> 00:37:45,200
depending on how the cues are managed,

992
00:37:43,280 --> 00:37:47,640
an O search may be necessary to

993
00:37:45,200 --> 00:37:50,320
determine the highest priority

994
00:37:47,640 --> 00:37:52,160
process. In practice, it is often easier

995
00:37:50,320 --> 00:37:53,680
to have separate cues for each distinct

996
00:37:52,160 --> 00:37:55,720
priority.

997
00:37:53,680 --> 00:37:57,839
This is known as multi-level Q

998
00:37:55,720 --> 00:38:00,240
scheduling. And here there must be

999
00:37:57,839 --> 00:38:01,760
scheduling among the cues. One way is

1000
00:38:00,240 --> 00:38:04,400
the one being shown on the screen right

1001
00:38:01,760 --> 00:38:07,040
now. Each Q has absolute priority over

1002
00:38:04,400 --> 00:38:08,720
lower priority cues. Scheduling simply

1003
00:38:07,040 --> 00:38:11,839
dispatches the process in the highest

1004
00:38:08,720 --> 00:38:11,839
priority non-mpt

1005
00:38:13,880 --> 00:38:18,800
Q. But to avoid starving lower priority

1006
00:38:16,800 --> 00:38:21,200
cues, we could schedule cues in another

1007
00:38:18,800 --> 00:38:23,440
way. We can rotate the ready Q in a

1008
00:38:21,200 --> 00:38:25,119
roundroin fashion but dispatching a

1009
00:38:23,440 --> 00:38:27,599
different amount of processes in a row

1010
00:38:25,119 --> 00:38:30,880
depending on the priority of the queue

1011
00:38:27,599 --> 00:38:30,880
to time slice among the

1012
00:38:32,760 --> 00:38:37,119
cues. Multi-level Q scheduling is

1013
00:38:35,359 --> 00:38:39,200
commonly used to partition processes

1014
00:38:37,119 --> 00:38:41,119
into several separate cues based on the

1015
00:38:39,200 --> 00:38:42,720
process type making it better to

1016
00:38:41,119 --> 00:38:45,280
schedule processes with multiple

1017
00:38:42,720 --> 00:38:46,640
response time requirement. It even allow

1018
00:38:45,280 --> 00:38:49,760
us to use a different scheduling

1019
00:38:46,640 --> 00:38:51,440
algorithm for each Q. The foreground Q

1020
00:38:49,760 --> 00:38:53,280
might be scheduled by a roundroin

1021
00:38:51,440 --> 00:38:55,040
algorithm for example while the

1022
00:38:53,280 --> 00:38:57,800
background Q is scheduled by a first

1023
00:38:55,040 --> 00:39:00,000
come first serve

1024
00:38:57,800 --> 00:39:02,800
algorithm and that's basically what we

1025
00:39:00,000 --> 00:39:05,040
expect from a generalpurpose CPUuler to

1026
00:39:02,800 --> 00:39:06,880
give priority to interactive processes

1027
00:39:05,040 --> 00:39:08,119
but not to the point of starving lower

1028
00:39:06,880 --> 00:39:10,400
priority

1029
00:39:08,119 --> 00:39:12,880
ones. There's just one more issue to

1030
00:39:10,400 --> 00:39:14,720
address. In a typical multi-level Q

1031
00:39:12,880 --> 00:39:16,240
scheduling algorithm, processes are

1032
00:39:14,720 --> 00:39:18,560
permanently assigned to a queue when

1033
00:39:16,240 --> 00:39:20,720
they enter the system. This has the

1034
00:39:18,560 --> 00:39:22,800
advantage of low overhead, but it's also

1035
00:39:20,720 --> 00:39:25,079
inflexible because processes don't

1036
00:39:22,800 --> 00:39:27,480
behave the same way throughout their

1037
00:39:25,079 --> 00:39:29,599
lifetime. Take your email client for

1038
00:39:27,480 --> 00:39:31,599
example. Most of the time it runs

1039
00:39:29,599 --> 00:39:33,760
quietly in the background, occasionally

1040
00:39:31,599 --> 00:39:35,359
checking for new messages, but the

1041
00:39:33,760 --> 00:39:38,000
moment you bring it to the foreground,

1042
00:39:35,359 --> 00:39:41,280
you expect it to be fast and responsive.

1043
00:39:38,000 --> 00:39:44,320
Menus, buttons, forms, all need to react

1044
00:39:41,280 --> 00:39:46,320
instantly. A process's CPU usage pattern

1045
00:39:44,320 --> 00:39:48,359
and by extension its response time

1046
00:39:46,320 --> 00:39:50,880
requirements can change

1047
00:39:48,359 --> 00:39:52,640
dynamically. The multi-level feedback Q

1048
00:39:50,880 --> 00:39:54,119
algorithm was designed to adapt to these

1049
00:39:52,640 --> 00:39:56,800
dynamic changes in

1050
00:39:54,119 --> 00:39:58,720
behavior. Here's how it works. Every

1051
00:39:56,800 --> 00:40:01,119
process starts in the highest priority

1052
00:39:58,720 --> 00:40:03,200
queue. If a process completes its CPU

1053
00:40:01,119 --> 00:40:04,880
burst within a single time quantum, it

1054
00:40:03,200 --> 00:40:07,599
can return to that queue after finishing

1055
00:40:04,880 --> 00:40:09,599
its I/IO. If a process needs more CPU

1056
00:40:07,599 --> 00:40:12,200
time than allowed by the time quantum,

1057
00:40:09,599 --> 00:40:15,280
it's moved down to a lower priority

1058
00:40:12,200 --> 00:40:17,599
Q. Lower priority QES have larger time

1059
00:40:15,280 --> 00:40:20,320
quantums, and processes that behave more

1060
00:40:17,599 --> 00:40:22,480
like IO bound tasks can be moved back up

1061
00:40:20,320 --> 00:40:24,079
if they complete their CPU burst in less

1062
00:40:22,480 --> 00:40:26,800
time than the quantum assigned to the

1063
00:40:24,079 --> 00:40:26,800
higher priority

1064
00:40:28,040 --> 00:40:33,359
Q. Over time, processes that have short

1065
00:40:31,119 --> 00:40:36,640
CPU bursts will tend to stay in higher

1066
00:40:33,359 --> 00:40:38,480
priority cues. In contrast, CPUbound

1067
00:40:36,640 --> 00:40:41,040
processes will gradually sync to lower

1068
00:40:38,480 --> 00:40:42,880
priority cues. This is how the system

1069
00:40:41,040 --> 00:40:44,200
adjusts process priority based on

1070
00:40:42,880 --> 00:40:46,240
behavior

1071
00:40:44,200 --> 00:40:48,240
automatically. Keep in mind that this is

1072
00:40:46,240 --> 00:40:50,320
just one example of multi-level feedback

1073
00:40:48,240 --> 00:40:52,720
Q scheduling. It comes in many

1074
00:40:50,320 --> 00:40:55,119
variations or as I like to say all

1075
00:40:52,720 --> 00:40:57,119
colors and flavors. Not only can the

1076
00:40:55,119 --> 00:40:59,440
scheduling algorithm applied to each Q

1077
00:40:57,119 --> 00:41:01,280
differ, but also the criteria used to

1078
00:40:59,440 --> 00:41:04,000
decide when a process should be promoted

1079
00:41:01,280 --> 00:41:06,079
or demoted between cues.

1080
00:41:04,000 --> 00:41:08,319
For instance, instead of relying solely

1081
00:41:06,079 --> 00:41:10,560
on the most recently observed CPU burst

1082
00:41:08,319 --> 00:41:12,240
to adjust a process's priority, the

1083
00:41:10,560 --> 00:41:14,240
system could use a prediction based on

1084
00:41:12,240 --> 00:41:16,160
historical data, which might help

1085
00:41:14,240 --> 00:41:18,720
avoiding unnecessary Q switches in

1086
00:41:16,160 --> 00:41:21,000
response to isolated or unusual bursts,

1087
00:41:18,720 --> 00:41:23,280
whether extremely short or unexpectedly

1088
00:41:21,000 --> 00:41:25,280
long. If you've been paying attention,

1089
00:41:23,280 --> 00:41:27,599
you might be thinking, wait, aren't we

1090
00:41:25,280 --> 00:41:30,079
penalizing CPUbound processes just for

1091
00:41:27,599 --> 00:41:31,839
needing more CPU? It seems we are now

1092
00:41:30,079 --> 00:41:34,319
going against the original idea of

1093
00:41:31,839 --> 00:41:36,800
prioritizing more important processes.

1094
00:41:34,319 --> 00:41:38,960
Aging indeed can prevent starvation. But

1095
00:41:36,800 --> 00:41:42,079
still, once a process is recognized as

1096
00:41:38,960 --> 00:41:44,800
CPUbound, it will eventually be demoted.

1097
00:41:42,079 --> 00:41:46,560
What's the deal here? Well, this is very

1098
00:41:44,800 --> 00:41:48,960
hard to explain without a 40 minutes

1099
00:41:46,560 --> 00:41:50,640
master class on processes analysis. The

1100
00:41:48,960 --> 00:41:52,319
best I can do now is to highlight two

1101
00:41:50,640 --> 00:41:54,560
important facts.

1102
00:41:52,319 --> 00:41:56,720
IObound and interactive processes are

1103
00:41:54,560 --> 00:41:58,920
not necessarily the same thing, but both

1104
00:41:56,720 --> 00:42:02,000
are characterized by very short CPU

1105
00:41:58,920 --> 00:42:04,640
